summary.seg: Cambridge, Sidney Sussex College MS 95, the largest known extant collection of Miracles of the Virgin, contains close to five hundred miracle stories. R. W. Southern, J. C. Jennings and others have mentioned it in passing; otherwise, this manuscript has excited little scholarly attention. Although catalogued by M. R. James in 1895, the collection has only recently been transcribed. It has a number of characteristics that raise questions about the transmission of large Marian miracle collections, and Marian piety on the verge of the Reformation. Dating from early-fifteenth century England, the manuscript is written in Latin, and has monastic associations.

Legends or Miracles of the Virgin describe Mary's intervention in the lives of ordinary mortals. These stories, told throughout Christendom, became one of the most prevalent forms of medieval popular literature. Over 500 different miracle stories have been catalogued to date in the CMMV. At least 100 manuscripts containing Marian legend collections remain extant. Told in vernacular languages as well as in Latin, Marian legends reflect in words and visual images the pietistic experiences of the faithful. From early Christianity, the faithful regarded Mary as miraculous by virtue of her virginal conception of Jesus. As beliefs about her evolved over the centuries, she took on an increasing number of miraculous and regal attributes. By the high middle ages she reigned in the hearts and minds of medieval faithful as Queen of Heaven. Medieval England, in particular, displayed profound devotion to the Virgin as documented by Edmund Waterton in Pietas Mariana Britannica (1879) and Gail Gibson in The Theater of Devotion: East Anglian Drama and Society in the Late Middle Ages (1989). Exploring these stories in their various facets, identifying groups or families of legends within the larger context of the miracle genre and the historical and cultural circumstances that saw their creation, offers the opportunity to increase understanding of Mary's place not only within the ecclesiastical structure, but in the lives of common folk.

That such a collection was made in the early fifteenth century indicates that Marian piety was not on the wane. Encyclopedic in its scope and clearly directed at an educated audience (as indicated by use of Latin at a time when miracles were being collected in the vernacular), this collections and those that served as its source, must have provided exempla for sermons, refectory reading material and texts for study and devotional purposes. A closer examination of the manuscript will yield valuable information about the intended audience, compilers and possible uses of individual tales and the collection, and thus lead us to a greater understanding of miracles of the Virgin and the Marian piety they promote.

msItem.title: Miracles of the Blessed Virgin Mary
msItem.rubric: 1r Incipit prologus prime partis tractatus miraculorum beate et perpeute virginis Marie genetricis dei per quemdam monachum de Thorne diuersis ex libris collecti et in hanc formam ad laudem eiusdem virginis redacti. Anno domini Millesimo cccc mo ix
msItem.incipit: 1r Eterna dei sapiencia attingens a fine usque ad finem fortiter et disponens queque suauiter
msItem.note: Book 1 begins on fol. 1v and contains 101 chapters; Book 2 begins on fol. 43v and contains 100 chapters; Book 3 begins on fol. 94v and contains 87 chapters; Book 4 begins on fol. 136r and contains 105 chapters; Book 5 begins on fol. 193r and contains 106 chapters

There is a table of contents for the work (incomplete at the beginning) on fols 220r-226v which is transcribed in M. R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the manuscripts in the library of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge (Cambridge, 1895), pp. 78-109.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern pencil foliation in the top right corner of each recto.

collation.p:
The MS consists of 29 quires:
One paper flyleaf
One parchment flyleaf
Quire j 8
Quires k 8 -t 8
Quire v 8
Quires x 8 -z 8
Quires 1 8 -9 8
Quire 0 8
Quire 11 8 -12 8 ; quires 13 and 14 are missing
Quire 15 8 , wanting leaves 4 and 5
Quire 16 4
One parchment flyleaf
One paper flyleaf
Quire signatures are present at the bottom centre of the first leaf of each quire.

James speculates (p. 77) that the manuscript originally had 308 leaves: it is missing eight quires of 8 at the beginning (quires a-h), quires 13 and 14 and two leaves from quire 15, giving a total of 82 missing leaves.

decoNote.p: 1r Initial outline in ink of a monk kneeling to the crowned Virgin; Christ as a child on her knee blessing him.
1r Page framed in gold, pink and blue. Similar but plainer frames at the beginnings of several of the books, e.g. fol. 138r.
Three-line initials at the start of each miracle in blue with red penwork, occasionally embellished with figures or faces, eg fols 142v, 177v, 180v.

additions.p: Sixteenth-century note on front flyleaf: hic liber continebat in se trescenta folia optimae membranae .

bindingDesc.p: Eighteenth-century blind-tooled brown leather over pasteboards. The back flyleaf shows traces of two clasps and a chain-mark.

origin.p: The opening rubric suggests that the manuscript was written by a monk of Thorney Abbey but the words de Thorne are written over an erasure. Pamela Robinson rejects the 1409 date and suggests that it probably derives from the exemplar and is not that of this copy ( Catalogue of dated and datable manuscripts c. 737-1600 in Cambridge Libraries , p. 111).

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by George Rayner in the sixteenth century. A note in the upper margin of fol. 1r reads: George Rayner of Peterborough pretium xx s . Rayner's name appears in the margins periodically throughout the manuscript.

The college's Register records the donation of the volume to the college by John Clement (BA 1611-12, MA 1614): Ex dono venerabilis viri Ioannis Clement Artium magistri ecclesiae de Chesterton in Com. Huntingdonensi rectoris dicti collegii quondam scholaris. Anno Dom. 1631 ( Registrum Bibliothecae , p. 102). The details are also pasted onto the inside front cover. Clement also donated a Bible (MS 96), which also has an ownership inscription of George Rayner, and a copy of the work of Richard Fitzralph (MS 64) to the college.
